# Aftermath

Besides the continued protests at the Times building, here's a few things that have happened in the months after the investigation's publish date:

- [Ventilation to Be Required in All New York Nail Salons](http://www.nytimes.com/2016/07/22/nyregion/ventilation-to-be-required-in-all-new-york-nail-salons.html)
- [Backed by Nail Salon Owners, a New York Legislator Now Fights Reforms](http://www.nytimes.com/2015/11/09/nyregion/once-behind-nail-salon-law-assemblyman-now-opposes-reforms.html)


The best thing I've read that follows Maslin Nir's investigation is an independent followup by the [Columbia Journalism Review's Chava Gourarie](http://www.cjr.org/investigation/new_york_times_nail_salon_investigation.php). Barring a shocking/scandalous revelation, it's safe to assume that the NYT will eagerly report on the positive effects of its investigation. Gourarie's 3,500-word article is largely favorable to Nir's work, but the indepth interview of salon workers and how they live day-to-day paints an authentic portrait of what a big news blast can and can't change to the people in the middle.



# The Pushback

I'm having trouble thinking of other NYT investigations that attracted so much pushback in protest and in words. More than a [year later](http://www.politico.com/media/story/2016/08/nail-salon-owners-are-still-protesting-the-new-york-times-004704), nail salon owners were *still* holding protests in front of the NYT building. For comparison, the [world-famous Occupy Wall Street protests lasted 2 months](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Timeline_of_Occupy_Wall_Street).

The most prominent rebuttal came from [Richard Bernstein](http://www.nybooks.com/daily/2015/07/25/nail-salons-new-york-times-got-wrong/), who is not only a former New York Times journalist, but with his wife, has owned and operated day spas for a dozen years in Manhattan. Unlike Nir, Bernstein and his wife are fluent in Chinese, and he attempted without success to find the same Chinese-language ads that Nir reportedly found: [What the ‘Times’ Got Wrong About Nail Salons](http://www.nybooks.com/daily/2015/07/25/nail-salons-new-york-times-got-wrong/)



The NYT's editors [replied in a press release](http://www.nytco.com/rebuttal-to-the-nybrs-article-on-nyt-nail-salon-series/), arguing that Bernstein has no ability to be objective on the topic, while pointing out that his inability to find the ads that Nir found proved little. 

Bernstein sent a second rebuttal a few days later: [Nail Salons: A Reply to the ‘Times’](http://www.nybooks.com/daily/2015/07/31/nail-salons-reply-times/)

